<text>Today's hiking should be a lot easier than yesterday.  Though we have almost 10 miles to go to Tuolumne, we don't have very much up and down.  It should only be about a 400' climb up to Cathedral Pass and then a descent into Tuolumne.  Of course, the real trail is always more up/down than just that, but overall it should be an easy day which I think we are all glad for as yesterday was a hard initiation day into the rigors of altitude and longer mileage days.

We're close enough to the high sierra camp at Sunrise that we can actually hear the horn they blow when meals are ready.  We can't see it, but it must not be too far away.  On to Tuolumne Meadows. It takes only minutes until we arrive at the Sunrise High Sierra Camp and we stop briefly there to look around.   There's a water faucet, a small store, a mess hall that looks like it could hold 30-40 people and tent cabins.  It's a beautiful location next to a big meadow with nice cathedral spires around.  In talking to one of the guests staying there, it's a lottery system.  There are zillions of people applying for only a few spots and it's pretty lucky if you actually get in.  The general idea is that you hike in to the camp and then use it as a home base for day trips.  They feed you and provide shelter.  I think you can either carry your own gear in or have your gear brought in on mules.

As we leave Sunrise, there's a walk through an appropriately named "Long Meadow" and I'm busy capturing photos of various views of the meadow with Cathedral Peaks in the background.  Then we start climbing up to Cathedral Pass which turns out to be a fairly short climb.  Once up at the pass, we get even nicer views of the high country and we head on towards Cathedral Lakes.  Once on the other side of Cathedral Pass nearer to Cathedral Lakes, we start to run into a lot more hikers, all coming from Tuolumne.  Some are overnight hikers based out of Tuolumne and some are day hikers.  Though I'd be hard pressed to say it was now crowded, I have come to appreciate it when there are fewer people.  We stop near one of the lakes for an extended break and a snack (though it's still relatively early in the day).</text>

